  "text": "The Firefox TLS handshake chain traces as follows:\n\n1. **Necko HTTP layer** (`netwerk/protocol/http/TlsHandshaker.cpp`): The `TlsHandshaker` class (owned by `nsHttpConnection`) is the entry point. Its `SetupSSL()` and `InitSSLParams()` methods configure the TLS parameters for HTTPS connections. `nsHttpConnection` holds a `nsISocketTransport` and uses `TlsHandshaker::InitSSLParams` to set up ALPN, NPN lists, and call into the NSS socket layer.\n\n2. **NSS IO Layer bridge** (`security/manager/ssl/nsNSSIOLayer.h` and `nsNSSIOLayer.cpp`): The `nsSSLIOLayerHelpers` class (defined in `nsNSSIOLayer.h`) is the bridge between Necko and NSS. Despite what the task description suggests about `netwerk/socket/`, this class actually lives in `security/manager/ssl/nsNSSIOLayer.h`. It provides helper methods and state for TLS intolerance, fallback, etc. The free functions `nsSSLIOLayerNewSocket()` and `nsSSLIOLayerAddToSocket()` (declared in `nsNSSIOLayer.h`, implemented in `nsNSSIOLayer.cpp`) are called by `nsSSLSocketProvider` and `nsTLSSocketProvider` to attach the NSS IO layer to a NSPR file descriptor.\n\n3. **NSS IO Layer implementation** (`security/manager/ssl/nsNSSIOLayer.cpp`): This file implements the actual NSPR IO layer using NSS (`nsSSLIOLayerAddToSocket`, `nsSSLIOLayerNewSocket`). It creates `NSSSocketControl` objects, installs the NSS PRFD layer, and hooks callbacks for certificate verification and client auth.\n\n4. **NSS TLS handshake** (`security/nss/lib/ssl/sslsecur.c` and `ssl3con.c`): The actual TLS handshake is performed in NSS. `sslsecur.c` contains `ssl_Do1stHandshake()` and `SSL_ForceHandshake()`, which drive the state machine. `ssl3con.c` contains the TLS 1.2 and older handshake implementations including `ssl3_SendClientHello`, `ssl3_HandleServerHello`, and the record-handling functions. `tls13con.c` handles TLS 1.3 specifically."
}

